lth service providers who refer migrants to the clinic and who tend to frame "migrant suffering" as a problem of integration that requires cultural expertise to address. In this context, Larchanché describes how staff members at Minkowska struggle to promote cultural competence, which offers a culturally and linguistically sensitive approach to care while simultaneously addressing the broader structural factors that impact migrants’ mental health. Ultimately, Larchanché identifies practical routes for improving caregiving practices and promoting hospitality—including professional training, action research, and advocacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEmigration and immigrationxPsychological aspects. 0aEthnopsychologyxMethodology. 0aMental health serviceszFrancezParis. 0aMental health services. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Anxieties, Centre Minkowska, clinic, psychology, anthropologist, Paris, France, Stéphanie Larchanché, immigrants, mental healthcare, immigration policy, limited resources, social anxieties, social services, health services, migrant suffering, mental health, professional training, action research, advocacy, Ethical Double-Binds, Migrant Youth, Cultural Competence, psychotherapy, Public Health, Human Right, Anthropology, health policy, Ethnopsychology, disease, health issues, immigration, emigration, social science, Medical Anthropology, cultural, linguistic differences.1 aManderson, Lenore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070480808iT